{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_hatra_ver01/data/sn86091197/00279550973/1924042401/0566.xml":{"full_text":"\u00aeI 3\u00f6alyn Wivpxtblxmn\nt*\n$2 a Year\nBLACKFOOT, IDAHO, APRIL 24, 1924\nVol. XX, No. 17\n$10,000 FIRE\nAT FORT HALL\nDairy Bam, Twenty-three Head\n1 J\nof Cows and Farm Machinery\nCompletely Destroyed\n\nA fire, believed to have been of in\ncendiary origin, completely de\nstroyed the new |5000 dairy barn at\nthe Ft. Hall Indian agency school\nat 12.30 Wednesday morning. In\naddition to the total destruction of\nthe barn, twenty-three head of reg\nistered Holstein cows and a quantity\nThe\nof farm machinery was lost,\ndamage, according to agency officials,\n\nwill amount to approximately 10\n000\nThe barn was a two story structure\nand was completed only last August.\nIt was modern in every respect and\nthe basement portion was used for\nhousing the registered stock. -The\nsecond floor or loft was used for\nstorage purposes.\nThe building was a mass of flames\nwhen the fire was discovered at\n12.30 Wednesday morning and had\nno doubt been burning for some lit\ntle time. The large fire gong was\nsounded and the boys in the dormi\ntory, which is a short distance from\nthe barn, lost no time- in getting out\nand fighting the blaze. The Indian\nboys fought the blaze barefooted,\nand were directed in their work by\nW. Dias, principal at the agency\nschool. Two lines of hose were in\noperation within two kninutes after\nthe fire gong sounded and altho the\nwater pressure was good, the fire had\ngained too much headway to be con\ntrolled.\nSi\nTwo of the large doors in the base\nment of the barn were closed late\nthe evening before and the finding\nof these doors open and the fact that\nthe fire started in the loft, leads the\nagency officials to believe that the\nbarn was set afire.\nThe badly burned carcasses of the\ntwenty-three head of Holstein cows\nwere found in the stalls in the base\nment. The fire had gained such\nheadway by the time it was dis\ncovered that it was impossible to get\nany of the registered stock out of the\nburning structure.\n\nPLEASED WITH HOLSTEINS\nPete ana Chris Larson, who live\non route three, went broke feeding\nsteers three or four years ago, and\nhave since been soft-pedaling ex\npenses because there was no money\non hand.\nAbout the first of March, 1924,\nthey bought eleven Holstein cows in\ncache valley and are rebuilding their\nfortunes slowly. They are very well\npleased with the cows and with the\nmilk checks.\n\u00a3tatrmrnt nf (Ennhitimt\nRendered to the State Banking Department and to the\nFederal Reserve Bank at the close of business\nMarch 31, 1924\nResources\n246 771.18\n1 800.00\n11 536.60\n23 034-38\n11 485.82\n96.58\nLoans and Discounts\nFederal Reserve Stock\nFurniture and Fixtures\nReal Estate\nJudgments .-..1--\u2014.\u2014.\nOverdrafts\nLiberty Bonds and Warrants 51,927.63\nCash and Sight Exchange..\u00bb.. 87,473.68\nAvailable Cash\nOther Assets\n139.401.31\n817.61\ni 39 4 OI. 3 i\n$434,943-48\nTotal\nLiabilities\nCapital\nSurplus\nReserve for Depreciation\nDeposits\nBills Payable\nRediscounts\n50,000.00\n10,000.00\n489.03\n374 454-45\nNONE\nNONE\n434 943-48\nTotal\nBanking methods and practice may change with\nthe years, but those qualities which make for caution\nand prudence in handling the money of others permit\nno modification.\nA conservative bank is the place to deposit your money\nllarkfimt (Citij Sank\nIdaho Coal\nFor Idahoans\nAn interesting meeting was held\nat the Chamber of Commerce Rooms\nwhen H. F. Samuels, president of the\nTeton Coal company, delivered an\naddress on the subject of cheaper\nThis\ncoal for southeastern Idaho,\nis a matter of vital importance to\nevery citizen of this community and\nshould be considered by all loyal\ncitizens as demanding personal at\ntention.\nThe contention of the O. S. L. that\nthe coal is not of good quality seems\nto be without foundation, in fact, on\nthe other hand the Teton Basin coal\nwould seem to have much greater\nheating qualities than the coal we\nare at present being supplied with,\nand the Teton Coal company is now\nin position to mine coal in commer\ncial quantities, all that is lacking is\nthe transportation facilities.\nThe coal In Teton Basin was con\nsidered of sufficient value during\nthe war to warrant the federal gov\nernment in building a spur from the\nmain line of the O. S. L. to the mine,\nat a cost of something like 2200 000\nWhen the O. S. L. resumed control\nof its system this spur was taken\nover as \"Junk\" and the federal gov\nernment reimbursed in the amount\nof between $30,000 and $38,000.\nThe O. S. L. is now proposing to\nwreck this spur which the federal\ngovernment built, pull up the tracks\nand leave the mine with no possiblity\nof transportation for Us output.\nThe Idaho Utilities Commission\nwill hold a meeting at Driggs on May\n2 to hear arguments on both sides\nand the various chambers of com\nmerce from Blackfoot north, includ\ning St. Anthony, Victor, Driggs,\nRigby, Rexburg, Dubois, Idaho Falls,\nand Shelley have each endorsed the\nresolution urging the utilities com\nmission to require the O. S. L. to re\npair the spur, provide cars and all\ntransportation facilities for the Teton\nCoal company, to the end that the\ncitizens of southeastern Idaho may\nbe provided with cheaper and better\ncoal.\u2014Evening Bulletin.\n\nSTARTING HUNGARIAN QUAIL\nThe fish and game department of\nIdaho imported forty-five pairs of\nHungarian quail from Europe re\ncently at a cost of $11 a pair plus a\ndollar for import duty, and Bingham\ncounty received three pairs of them.\nOne of the birds died after arriving\nhere last week.\n'1 nese ouails are said to be very\nhardy birds, but captivity is fatal to\nthem if they are confined very long.\nThere are the size of the American\nquail, but have the color of the sage\nhen, so when seen In proper season\nthey will likely pass for sage chicks.\n\nHamilton Wright, George F. Ga\ngon and Wendell Gagon are at Boise\nfor the trial of W. F. Berryman.\nThe L .D. S. Uunlversity Glee club\nof Salt Lake gave a concert at the\ntabernacle on Wednesday evening.\nBINGHAM COUNTY\nFORGING AHEAD\nMuch Road Construction During Panic, and\nBooks and Finances in Excellent Condition,\nSays Expert Accountant.\nPolitical Parties Receive Warm Commendation\nAfter a Complete Audit of All the Books.\nOfficials of Both\nA board of county commissioners, who went into\noffice by small majority and with/ doubtful support from\nthe general public, have achieved diplomatic victories,\nput the county finances in shape and pushed road con\nstruction projects, getting state and federal aid not\nconsidered possible when they went into office three and\na half years ago. New state and federal road projects\nin prospect, county fair property preserved and fair in\ndebtedness almost cleaned up.\nThe firm of Defenbach Moon ex\npert public accountants, who six\nyears ago discovered and exposed\nembezzlements in our county, city\nand school funds that had been suc\ncessfully accomplished and con\ncealed from other audits, have just\ncompleted and filed the report of\ntheir 1923 audit. Under their direc\ntion, many changes were made in the\nmanner of keeping the records, and\nnow they record their approval of\nthe way the books are kept .and af\nfirm under oath that every dollar of\nthe county money is where It be\nlongs.\nWith a sharp shrinkage In the\namount of taxes paid in, and the\namount of money available for road\npurposes, the board of commission\ners have protected the investment\nmade in roads in former years and\ncontinued construction both by the\nhome people and by joint state,\ncounty and federal projects. When\nthe panic started, the Yellowstone\nHighway thru Bingham county was\nin bad condition and the public was\nworried about the upkeep of the new\nroads they had built. Now the Yel\nlowstone Highway is graded and\npaved part way and graded and sur\nfaced the rest of the distance, has\nbeen turned over to the state high\nway department to maintain and.\nother sections of road in the county\nhave been taken over or are in pro\ncess of being taken over by the state\nto be maintained by state expense.\nSince January, 1921, the delin\nquent taxes have mounted from\n$189,000 to $559,000, thus withhold\n\nlng $370,000 from the county treas-]\nury because people did not have the\nmoney to pay it. but the county gov\nernment has gone on functioning and\nreduced the amount of its outstand\ning warrants and brought the price\nof warrants back to par. It is an in\nteresting story in the real life of\nBingham county and its people, and\nwill go down on the record as a bril\nliant achievement of three years fol\nlowing a mass meeting at the\nOrpheum, called for the purpose of\ndeclaring the people insolvent in the\nmatter of paying their taxes, but\nwhich turned into a \"can-and-will\"\nmeeting that adopted a resolution to\npay all the taxes possible, sustain\nthe public treasury to the limit of\npeople's ability, sustain the reputa\ntion of irrigated land to support its\npopulation and meet its bonds, to\nhold up the hands of our delegation\nin congress asking for appropriations\nfor reclamation, and to \"hold steady\nand not rock tba boat.\"\nThe Clouds are Lifting\nMany people have felt anxiety be\ncause it requires $30,000 a year to\npay the Interest charges on what is\nknown as the bond roads, and in\n1929 we shall begin paying $60,000\na year on the principal, and there\nafter less each year on interest\ncharges. It has been, a source of\nanxiety to know how we were to\nmeet the $90,000 payment at the\npeak year of 1929, but the answer\nto that is already taking form. The\ndelinquent taxes are piling up as a\nreservoir to furnisu money in future\nyears to meet just such demands. It\nis the history of county governments\nconfronted with the circumstances\nwe are now in, that If they can meet\ncurrent demands during a panic, the\naccumulated delinquent taxes and\nother sources of wealth that auto\nmatically flow into the public treas\nury with the return of prosperity,\nwill pay off the bonds and people do\nnot feel the weight of it. The road\nbonds referred to amount to $600,\n000 and the accumulated delinquent\ntaxes already amount to $559,000.\nMost of this amount will be paid,\nwhile property now being accumu\nlated by the county may eventually\nsell for enough to give large profits\nto the county. The experience of\nolder states going thru similar exper\niences bears out this prediction. An\nother hopeful and reassuring indica\ntion regarding the payment of delin\nquencies is that the Defenbach and\nMoon report for 1922 showed about\n$2900 in arrears on personal prop\nerty and during the year 1923 more\nthan $2600 of it was paid, this in the\nworst period of tho panic.\nBooks are Better Kept\nThe reports of these public ac\ncountants of former years usually\nshowed a confused condition regard\ning fees earned by different officers,\nbut not actually paid in and turned\ninto the treasury, and recommenda\ntions were made regarding the means\nby which collections might be made\nand fixing the responsibility for the\nloss of what could not be collected.\nOne official paid about $1100 to\nsquare up such matters, another was\ngiven time in which to collect what\nhe could, and one was given a rebate\nof $3.50 to cover errors he had made\nin favor of the county and against\nhimself. In the report just filed, the\naccountants take occasion to com\nmend every department for having\nits books in proper condition and\nmoney in place. Some very old\nclaims for fees earned and never col\nlected and uncollectable, the report\nsays should be cancelled.\n'the Money is There\nSpecial mention is made of the of\nfice of Sheriff A. B. Stephens for the\ngood condition of his accounts, also\nTreasurer Mrs. Margaret. Ward,\nwhere radical changes have been\nmade in the accounting system In the\npast three years, and the county\nclerk's office, H. A. Benson, whose\nrecords were received by him in good\ncondition and have been kept at\nhigh efficiency. His accounts bal\nanced and an unexpected remittance\nof a doubtful account by mail placed\na surplus dollar in the till. The ac\ncountants have devised a way for\ncarrying the account of delinquent\nt axe8 BO they are more acessible and\nnot liable to be overlooked and lost\nin the mass of records, and they\nrecommend that some additional\nhelp be employed temporarily in the\ncounty clerk's office to open up the\nset of books and place, all delinquent\naccounts in them so' they can be\nturned to by index without loss of\ntime or anxiety as to whether the ac\ncounts are complete. They give a\ndetailed report of which firms and\npersons are delinquent on personal\nproperty that ought to be collected,\nand which the assessor's bondsmen\nmay be held to account for.\nMore Thoro Assessment\nAside from the official report\ncomes the information that Assessor\nArthur Manwaring this year sought\nto accomplish what had not been\ndone before to the satisfaction of of\nficials and the people\u2014secure a com\nplete assessment of stock.being fed\nin transit and stock being fattened\nin the county for shipment or slaugh\nter and which would disappear be\nfor the deputy assessors would make\ntheir rounds in the usual way. The\ncommissioners kept their eyes on this\nadditional expense, noted the returns\nfrom It and the Justice of correctly\nand fairly distributing the tax bur\nden, and gave it their sanction.\nWas a Discouraging Outlook\nThe present board of commission\ners came into office over three years\nago Just when the panic was grow\ning serious. A hundred miles of new\ngrades had been built on tho high\nways, and it was considered import\nant that they should be cared for\nand repaired promptly whenever de\nfects showed, because while they\nwere new they would take damage\nrapidly if not kept in repair. There\nwas very little money for such use,\nand in 1921 the farmers were asked\nto drag the roads without cost to\nthe county. Much of this was done,\nand In 1922 the legislature passed\nact taking one-fifth of the avail\nable funds out of the hands of the\ncommissioners and applying it to In\nterest on state road bonds. They\nalso cut down the powers of the\nboard in the levies, and in this county\nit left the board about half as much\nmoney as they had at their command\nin previous years. There were press\ning demands for replacement of\nbridges and culverts and repairs\nwhere floods or other things made\nrepairs and extensions of roads nec\nIn some of the older parts\nwas\nan\nessary.\nof the county, where traffic\nheavy and people were well situated,\nthe commissioners declined to make\nnew grades asked for, but accepted\nthe offers of the people interested in\nthe projects, to pay half of the ex\nout of the county road fund.\npense\nwhere the people were willing to pay\nthe other half. In other words, the\ncounty managed the work thru its\nengineer and road superintendent,\nand paid the farmer laborer half rate\nfor their work. In this way five and\na half miles of new roads were built\nin the Thomas country, and four\nmiles were graveled in the Shelley\ndistrict. This plan is known as the\nlocal fifty-fifty plan.\n(Continued on page two)\nBlackfoot Sports\nmen to Plant Fish\nAbout fifty men met at the K. P.\nhall on Tuesday evening to receive\nthe report and suggestions of a com\nmutes from the Knights of Pythias\nlodge regarding the future activities\nfor stocking Bingham county streams\nwith fish. M. M. Farmer was the\nspokesman for the lodge and pre\nsided at the meeting. R. E. Thomas,\nstate game warden was present,\nfrom Boise, William Hayes, assist\nant chief deputy, of Pocatello, hav\ning charge of six of the southeastern\ncounties; Lewis Robbins, deputy\ngame warden of Bingham county:\nR. O. Graham, vice president of the\nIdaho Sportsmen's association, of Po\ncatello; Mr. Newcomb, president of\nthe Bannock County Sportsmen's as\nsociation, of Pocatello; A. J. Snyder,\nof Springfield; Elmer Stephens,\npresident of the Bingham County\nSportsmen's association, of Black\nfoot: Senator L. R. Thomas; C. C.\nClark, president of the Blackfoot\nChamber of Commerce, and many\nother local men.\nChairman Farmer reviewed the\nactivities of the K. P. lodge of the\npast year, planting fish in Wolverine\nand Brush creek, and said they have\nararnged with the fish and game de\narranged with the fish and game de\nclub to trap trout in our streams,\ntake the spawn and weekly transport\nthe product to the fish hatchery, re\nceive back half of the hatch and\ntransport them to the streams. In\nthis way they hope to plant half a\nmillion trout in our streams this\nyear, vastly more than could be ob\ntained without trapping the fish, and\nthe work is now under way. A trap\nhas just been built in Wolverine, and\nmen and materials are ready to go\nThe beavers have built hundreds\nof dams in the streams and thus\nmade a network of storage reservoirs\nwhere once the water ran oft without\ndelay. It is impossible for trout to\nget over the higher dams, so they\nwill be planted all along the stream\non to other creeks.\n\nahd left to multiply. In a few years\nall these streams will be a rich\npleasure ground for the public In\nstead of being depleted and barren\nas most of them are now. Blackfoot\nriver was once well stocked, but has\nbeen overdone by fishermen and not\nThe local clubs and\nendorsing the plan,\nRotary and the American Legion\nhaving just joined the movement,\nand by co-operation of all public\nspirited persons the work will be\ncarired out as rapidly as nature will,\npermit.\nA number of speakers responded,\nH. Early, Mr. Loveless, A. J.\nSnyder, C. C. Clark and Messrs. New-j\ncomb, Graham and Thomas, of Po- j\ncatello and Boise.\nBriefly stated, the work under\ntaken is to preserve the fish and\ngame for future generations as well\nas for the present, to destroy preda\ntory fish and birds that kill off or\nprevent the hatching of the valauble\nones, to govern people so that they\nmany remain,\nlodges are\n,T.\nwill be real sportsmen Instead of\nflsh hogs and mere slayers of fowls,\nto enforce the fish and game laws, to\nprotect pheasants and other fowl\nneeding fair play in summer and\nfeed In winter when snow lies deep,\nto train hunters to be more careful\npf human life, to exercise care to\nprotect stock in fields, to enter no\nfields or premises to hunt without\nthe owner's permission, and in gen\neral to stop the waste and irritations\narising from exercising the prevlleges\nof the sportsman.\nRalph Edmunds, of Idaho Falls,\nwho has been in California for two\nyears, writes to his home paper that\nwhile California is complaining of\nThey have such a strict\nA man\nFOOT AND MOUTH DISEASE\nthe embargo against shipping their\nfruit and vegetables into other states,\nthat they do not themselves take any\nsuch chances as they ask people of\nother states to take with their ship\nment.\nquarantine that a crockery dealer,\nwho received a shipment from\nEngland, had to unpack the crock\nery on the dock and burn all pack\ning there, bringing only the bare\ngoods up from the port,\nraising head lettuce for sale cannot\nship it from one California county to\nan adjoining county for consumption\nthere.\nMr. Edmunds says the disease is\na terrible thing and can be carried\non the tires of cars, on people's shoes\nor anything that it can stick to, and\nthat it spreads so easily and is so\ndeadly we should do everything pos\nsible to keep it out.\nFARMS FOR RENT\nI have several farms for rent in Bingham county. They\nare of different size and in various localities.- For par\nticulars communicate with\nBowen Curley, Idaho Falls\nCHAMBER OF COM\nMERCE MEETING\nGoodly Amount of Business and\nMuch Mirth Mark Regular\nMonthly Meeting\nof It are paved, which are surfaced\nand which are merely graded. They\nare preparing ,to print a large num\nber of them for distribution at cost,\nand expressed the hope that other\ntowns in the valley would appreciate\ntheir efforts and help the work\nalong,\nAt the monthly meeting of the\nChamber of Commerce held on\nThursday evening there were some\nout of town visitors and some jokes\nthrown in with the proceedings.\nAfter the routine business, Chairman\nC. C. Clark introduced C. C. Gigneau,\nthe assistant agriculturist for the\nUnion Pacific system, who talked on\ndairying and diversified farming as\na means of solving the freight rate\nproblems and others by keeping the\nheavy, bulky crops at home and ship\nping such concentrated products as\nbutter, cheese and eggs, supplying\nour home markets ourselves, instead\nof shipping products in from other\nstates.\nW. P. Havener, road engineer\nfrom Pocatello, talked on the need\nof a reliable road map to take the\nplace of the absurd productions that\nhave been used for the purpose of\nmaking certain towns or cities loom\nup as desirable points for tourists to\npass thru. He said the average map\nis a vicious misrepresentation of\ngeography, roads and conditions and\ndeceives rather than informing the\ntraveler.\nChamber of Commerce has been\nworking for a couple of weeks on a\nmap that is so designed that it shows\nthe actual position of the main roads,\nand by its legend shows which parts\nHe said the Pocatello\nJ. M. Hartong said he had studied\ntheir work carefully and considered\nit the be8t thing that had been pro\nduced f 0r a tourist guide,\nR 0 Graham, of Pocatello, former\nbull-whacker. mule-skinner and\nBtage dr Ve r said he just came along\nin the car to serve as ballast to make\nR r j de easy for the others, and they\nmade the run in one hour over the\n8 a jn a route they used to take two\ndayg for when he was freighting into\nMontana. He found It very gratlfy\nlng j ndeed to witness the changes of\nti me and to be with a gathering of\nmen who had organized to do public\nwork 8Uch a8 the individual cannot\naccomplish working alone. He said\ntourist camps have become a\nnecessary institution, but that the\nf roe tourist camp is passing.\ntourist wants good accommodations\nand W ants to pay for them; not a\nuigIl pr i cej but a fair price so he will\nnot feel t i la t he is anobject of charity\nwhen he is out to have a good time\nand t o spend some money,\ntourist camp of tomorrow will have\nThe\nTho\ngra88 and shade, good cooking ar\nrangements, shower baths of hot and\nco d wa t e r, sewer and other things\nfor 8 an itation, and 'police protection,\nAR of the8e things cost money and\nthe citizens who maintain them are\nentitled to be reimbursed by a sys\ntem of fee8 to be paid by the tourist,\np oca t e llo has a free camp ground\nt hat was donated by the Sportsmen's\na 880 C i at i 0 n, tho it is not much of a\ncamping ground, lacking some of the\nj comforts he had just named,\nBut\nbecause it had been donated by an\norganization, they had all felt out\nof place in suggesting arrangements\nto make it a pay station. The city\nis now preparing to have a larger and\nfiner park for that purpose,\nI\nter of a tourist information bureau\nfor Blackfoot, and asked a recon\nsideration of the vote of a month ago\naccepting floor space in the lobby of\nthe Eccles hotel, and leaving the de\ncision with the committee. He said\nthere were difficulties in the way of\nkeeping two offices open for Chamber\nof Commerce work, and they might\nhave to have the information bureau\nup stairs in the present headquarters\nto save employing two persons this\nyear, which is beyond our financial\nability. The vote carried, leaving\ndecision to the committee.\nThe question of changing the time\nof monthly meetings from Thursday\nto Monday evening was left unde\ncided.\nPocatello has employed a new\nsecretary for their Chamber of Com\nmerce, named Harader. He has been\nR. A. English reported on the mat\n(Continued on page twelve)","height":"20160","width":"14448"}}
